<DOC><DOCNO> AP900817-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-90 1631EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Bank-Turkey     08-17 0187</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Bank-Turkey,0194</SECOND><HEAD>Eximbank to Help U.S. Firm Compete for Big Helicopter Order</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. Export-Import Bank said Friday it isready to guarantee a $1.37 billion credit to help an Americanaerospace firm compete for a Turkish order of 200 helicopters.   The government-operated bank said it notified Congress of theloan guarantee after reviewing the international situation andevaluating Turkey's credit worthiness.   United Technologies Corp. of Hartford, Conn., is competing forthe order against Aerospatiale of France,Messerschmitt-Bolkow-Blohm GmbH of West Germany and Agusta ofItaly, the announcement said.   United Technologies hopes to sell the Turkish Defense Ministrykits for final assembly in Turkey between 1992-94 of 200 SikorskyUH-50L general utility helicopters expected to cost about $1.5billion, said the Bank.   The unarmed helicopters would be used for reconnaissance,medical evacuation and search and rescue.   The Bank said it is allowed by law to make an exception to itspolicy against financing military equipment sales. Under thatexception, the Bank may guarantee loans for commercial sales ofdefense hardware for Greece and Turkey provided the purchases arenot for use on Cyprus.</TEXT></DOC>